TableSeek.Name: CIC_Medium_Res_Ref_Filter
TableSeek.Description: TiMe constant for Medium Resolution reference filter in CIC.Values above 40-50 uSec. may filter out actual 24Xe signal athigh engine speed. MEDRES output from the CIC is delayed/skewedfrom the 24Xe input by approx. the amount of this calibration., Units:

TableSeek.Name: Engine_Schedule_RPM_Hi
TableSeek.Description: The engine speed above which some of the sync. code activation rate is changed., Units: RPM

TableSeek.Name: Engine_Schedule_RPM_Lo
TableSeek.Description: The engine speed below which some of the sync. code activation rate is changed., Units: RPM

TableSeek.Name: Engine_Identifier
TableSeek.Description: Describes the type of engine associated with the vehicle including the engine displacement and valve train geometry., Units: Engine_Identifier_Type
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: *** DO NOT CHANGE ***If you need to change this, swap the whole calibration block for a proper one.Defines what engine type this calibration is for:0=5.3L1=5.7L2=4.8L3=6.0L4=4.3L5=5.0L6=8.1L7=5.7L HO

TableSeek.Name: Number_Cylinders
TableSeek.Description: Number of cylinders for this engine application., Units: SHORTCARD
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: ** DO NOT CHANGE ***If you need to change this, swap the whole calibration block for a proper one.Defines the number of cylinders in the calibration.

TableSeek.Name: Low_Resolution_Reference_Angl
TableSeek.Description: Identifies the number of degrees from a low resolution pulse to Top Dead Center of the cylinder., Units: Degrees

TableSeek.Name: Type_Of_Knock_Sensors
TableSeek.Description: Identifies whether the engine is equipped with resonant( 0 ) or flat response( 1 ) knock sensors., Units: Knock_Sensor_Type
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: B1402 - Knock Sensor Type in use
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Unchecked = Resonant (LS1 type)Checked = Flat Response (LS2 and LS3 type)
TableSeek.ExtraCategories: Engine Calibration - Spark - Knock Sensor - Hardware

TableSeek.Name: Ambiguous_Cam_Transition_Low
TableSeek.Description: Cam sensor transition low limit based on 24X regions., Units: 24X Region

TableSeek.Name: Ambiguous_Cam_Transition_High
TableSeek.Description: Cam sensor transition high limit based on 24X regions., Units: 24X Region

TableSeek.Name: EGR_Air_Flow*01-
TableSeek.Description: EGR air flow through the EGR valve., Units: Grams Per Second
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: EGR air flow through the EGR valve.

TableSeek.Name: VE_Temperature
TableSeek.Description: Square root of the Kelvin inlet temperature at which volumetric efficiency tables were calibrated. Needed because volumetric efficiency is directly proportional to Square root of the Kelvin inlet temperature., Units: sqrt deg K
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Square root of the Kelvin inlet temperature at which volumetric efficiency tables were calibrated. Needed because volumetric efficiency is directly proportional to Square root of the Kelvin inlet temperature.

TableSeek.Name: Volumetric_Efficiency_Baro_Co
TableSeek.Description: Term used to correct barometric efficiency for the change in throttle and pumping efficiency of the engine as the barometric pressure varies., Units: NONE 0-2
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Engine VE for calculating engine fueling during engine cranking.

TableSeek.Name: Volumetric_Efficiency_Crank
TableSeek.Description: Volumetric efficiency at cranking speeds., Units: Percent
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Engine VE for calculating engine fueling during engine cranking.

TableSeek.Name: K_Main_Volumetric_Efficiency_%
TableSeek.Description: The volumetric efficiency term used for modeling the air per cylinder for Dyna-Air calculations., Units: gm*K/kPa
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Main volumetric efficiency table.The values in this table represent the efficiency of the engine's ability to fill the cylinders with air.It is used to predict the volume of air entering each cylinder under varying conditions.The air mass per cylinder can be determined from the VE table using the following formula:g/cyl = VE*MAP/charge temperatureVe is in g*K/kPa,MAP is in kPa,charge temperature is in degrees Kelvin.Cylinder volume is used to calculate the VE as a percentage.Changing the cylinder volume will change the VE percentages displayed in this table.

TableSeek.Name: K_Main_Volumetric_Efficiency
TableSeek.Description: The volumetric efficiency term used for modeling the air per cylinder for Dyna-Air calculations., Units: gm*K/kPa
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Main volumetric efficiency table.The values in this table represent the efficiency of the engine's ability to fill the cylinders with air.It is used to predict the volume of air entering each cylinder under varying conditions.The air mass per cylinder can be determined from the VE table using the following formula:g/cyl = VE*MAP/charge temperatureVe is in g*K/kPa,MAP is in kPa,charge temperature is in degrees Kelvin.Cylinder volume is used to calculate the VE as a percentage.Changing the cylinder volume will change the VE percentages displayed in this table.

TableSeek.Name: Gamma_Init_Coolant_Breakpoint
TableSeek.Description: Breakpoints for selection coolant zone for initializing Filtered_VE_Correction_Factor., Units: Deg C
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: VE Correction Initial Factor Zone ECT Boundaries
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Breakpoints for selection coolant zone for initializing Filtered_VE_Correction_Factor.

TableSeek.Name: Gamma_Init_Table
TableSeek.Description: Initialize Filtered_VE_Correction_Factor to this value., Units: NONE 0-2
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: VE Correction Initial Factor Zone MAP Boundaries
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Initialize Filtered_VE_Correction_Factor to this value.

TableSeek.Name: K_Cylinder_Volume
TableSeek.Description: Volume of each cylinder in the engine., Units: Liter
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Defines the volume in liters of each cylinder in the engine.

TableSeek.Name: Backup_Air_Flow_Filter_Coef
TableSeek.Description: Use this to filter air flow sensor reading to generate air flow 'prediction' in response to MAP OR TPS failure., Units: NONE 0-1
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Use this to filter air flow sensor reading to generate air flow 'prediction' in response to MAP OR TPS failure.

TableSeek.Name: Hi_Speed_Dyna_Air_Thresh
TableSeek.Description: Engine speed above which a filtered value OF Sensed_Air_Per_Cylinder is used instead of the Dyna-Air prediction., Units: RPM
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: B0120 - Dynamic Airflow Max RPM Threshold
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: If engine speed is less than this value, then the PCM uses a dynamically calculated airflow value to determine grams of air per cylinder.While the airflow is in a "steady state", then a correction factor is updated based on the airflow difference between the MAF sensed airflow and the MAP calculated airflow.During rapid changes in airflow, the correction factor is applied to the airflow calculations to compensate.If engine speed is above this value, then the PCM will use the MAF sensor exclusively (if not disabled by DTCs) to calculate grams of air per cylinder.No updates are made to the airflow correction factor.

TableSeek.Name: Hi_Speed_Dyna_Air_Hysteresis
TableSeek.Description: Amount by which engine speed must drop below KE_Hi_Speed_Dyna_Air_Thresh before the Dyna_Air prediction is used again., Units: RPM
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: If engine speed is lower than B0120 by this value, then the PCM goes back to using a dynamically calculated airflow value to determine grams of air per cylinder.

TableSeek.Name: Use_Charge_Temperature*01-
TableSeek.Description: Determines if the inlet charge temperature prediction or the induction air temperature sensor value will be used in Dyna-Air. If set to TRUE, inlet charge temperature is used. If FALSE, induction air temperature is used., Units: Boolean
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Yes means the PCM will blend IAT and ECT to determine the charge temperature of the air entering the cylinder, used in VE calculations.No means the PCM will use the IAT exclusively as the charge temperature.The blend weighting between IAT and ECT is determined by {B4901} "Charge Temperature Blending".

TableSeek.Name: Injector_Slope*01-03
TableSeek.Description: Defines the slope of the injector versus on time., Units: Grams/Sec
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Flow rate of the fuel injectors.If the fuel rail pressure is NOT referenced to manifold pressure, then decreasing the manifold pressure has the same effect as increasing the fuel rail pressure. The fuel flow rate of the injectors will increase at higher manifold vacuums (i.e. lower manifold pressure).This table calibrates the flow rate of the injectors at various manifold VACUUM levels.It is based on manifold absolute VACUUM, where:0 kPa vacuum indicates atmosphere and80 kPa vacuum indicates atmosphere less 80kPa which, at sea level, is 101.3-80 = 21.3 kPa MAP.

TableSeek.Name: Short_Pulse_Adjustment
TableSeek.Description: Adjustment to pulse which is smaller than KE_Short_Pulse_ Limit based on the calculated pulse width (used by both SCPI and SFI system)., Units: Milliseconds
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: When a very short injector on time is commanded (between 0 - 4mS) the PCM will add the values in this table onto the injector on time.

TableSeek.Name: CL_Mode
TableSeek.Description: This calibration is a re-mapping of Mass_Airflow. Used as the independent variable for functions normally thought of as based on air flow rate., Units: NONE 0-64
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Tracks the measured/predicted engine airflow to determine which closed loop mode to use.Closed loop Airflow rate is used to define ranges of airflow in order to minimise the size of calibration tables that would otherwise contain as many rows as this table.

TableSeek.Name: Integral_Delay_Base_Lean*04-05
TableSeek.RowHeaders: CL Mode 00,CL Mode 08,CL Mode 16,CL Mode 24,CL Mode 32,CL Mode 40,CL Mode 48,CL Mode 56,CL Mode 64
TableSeek.Description: Base factor applied to the Integral_Delay_Base when both Slow and Fast O2 status are LEAN., Units: Seconds
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Determine the rate at which the STFT is updated by the PCM.These values are further adjusted by the multipliers in {B4114} "STFT Delay Multiplier".The O2 sensor voltages provide the PCM with the raw "Rich or Lean" data that it uses to periodically adjust the Short Term Fuel Trims.Even though the O2 sensors are sampled by the PCM up to 80 times per second, the Short Term Fuel Trim (STFT) is computed and updated by the PCM at varying rates.The rate at which the STFT is updated, ultimately depends on the engine's airflow (via {B4107} "Closed Loop Mode")and the STFT delay tables: - {B4113} STFT Base Delay - {B4114} STFT Delay Multiplier.

TableSeek.Name: Integral_Delay_Base_Lean*06-07
TableSeek.RowHeaders: CL Mode 00,CL Mode 08,CL Mode 16,CL Mode 24,CL Mode 32,CL Mode 40,CL Mode 48,CL Mode 56,CL Mode 64

TableSeek.Name: Integral_Delay_Base_Rich*1mb
TableSeek.RowHeaders: CL Mode 00,CL Mode 08,CL Mode 16,CL Mode 24,CL Mode 32,CL Mode 40,CL Mode 48,CL Mode 56,CL Mode 64
TableSeek.Description: Base factor applied to the Integral_Delay_Base when both Slow and Fast O2 status are RICH., Units: Seconds

TableSeek.Name: Integral_Delay_Gain_Lean*04-05
TableSeek.Description: Gain factor applied to the Integral_Delay_Base when both Slow and Fast O2 status are LEAN., Units: NONE 0-2
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: These values are the multipliers applied to {B4113} "STFT Base Delay".Based on the magnitude of the difference between the O2 millivolts and the {B4105} "O2 Switch point".The O2 sensor voltages provide the PCM with the raw "Rich or Lean" data that it uses to periodically adjust the Short Term Fuel Trims.Even though the O2 sensors are sampled by the PCM up to 80 times per second, the Short Term Fuel Trim (STFT) is computed and updated by the PCM at varying rates.The rate at which the STFT is updated, ultimately depends on the engine's airflow (via {B4107} "Closed Loop Mode")and the STFT delay tables: - {B4113} STFT Base Delay - {B4114} STFT Delay Multiplier.

TableSeek.Name: Integral_Delay_Gain_Lean*06-07
TableSeek.Description: Gain factor applied to the Integral_Delay_Base when both Slow and Fast O2 status are LEAN., Units: NONE 0-2

TableSeek.Name: Integral_Delay_Gain_Rich*1mb
TableSeek.Description: Gain factor applied to the Integral_Delay_Base when both Slow and Fast O2 status are RICH., Units: NONE 0-2

TableSeek.Name: Proportional_Term_Idle_Enable*99-
TableSeek.Description: Use specially formed idle proportional term at idle., Units: TRUE,FALSE
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: If set to Enable, then the PCM will use theSTFT idle tables: - {B4109} STFT Base Correction at Idle - {B4110} STFT Multiplier at Idleto compute the STFT when all closed loop idle parameters* are met.If set to Disable, then the PCM will use theSTFT non-Idle tables: - {B4111} STFT Base Correction at Non-Idle - {B4112} STFT Multiplier at Non-Idleto compute the STFT when all closed loop idle parameters* are met.* Closed loop idle parameters: - {B4101} Closed Loop Idle Vehicle Speed - {B4102} Closed Loop Idle Vehicle Speed Hysteresis - {B4103} Closed Loop Idle Throttle Position - {B4104} Closed Loop Idle Throttle Position Hysteresis

TableSeek.Description: Determines what the charge temperature is for the speed density fuel calculation, should be square root of the Inlet_Charge_Temerature in Kelvin, Units: Sqrt(Kelvin)
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Used to calculate absolute air charge temperature in degrees Kelvin.

TableSeek.Name: Charge_Temperature_Bias*01-
TableSeek.Description: Determines how close to either coolant temperature or air temperature the inlet charge temperature is estimated. At low flow, the charge temperature is closer to coolant, Units: NONE 0-2
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: The PCM calculates the charge temperature (in degrees Kelvin) using the following formula273.15+IAT+((ECT-IAT)*factor) where factor is obtained from this calibration.At low airflow "factor" is closer to 1 which weights the charge temperature in favour of ECT.At high airflow (>150g/s) "factor" is closer to 0 which weights the charge temperature in favour of IAT.The theory being that heat (ECT) is transferred from the heads and manifold after the IAT has been measured and prior to the air entering the cylinder.If factor is 0, then the charge temperature will be IAT, if factor is 1, then the charge temperature will be ECT, other values for factor will blend the charge temperature between IAT and ECT accordingly.This calibration is controlled by {B0109} "Blend IAT With ECT".

TableSeek.Name: Charge_Temperature_Filter*01-
TableSeek.Description: Determines how quickly a newly calculated inlet charge temperature is filtered into the old calculation. At low flow, the filter is slower than at high flows., Units: NONE 0-1
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Determines the rate of change of the calculated charge temperature in response to changes in the IAT or the ECT.Values closer to 1 will cause faster changes, values closer to 0 will cause slower changes.

TableSeek.Name: Knock_Detector_MAD_Init*01-
TableSeek.Description: Initialization value for Knock_Detector_MAD value invoked during powerup., Units: Millivolts
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: This is the initial threshold level for the knock sensors.The knock sensor threshold values are learned, based on previous knock sensor values. Each knock sensor learns its own unique threshold.The learned thresholds are multiplied by two multipliers (determined by operating conditions). The average background noise is then added to determine the calculated thresholds.The calculated thresholds are compared with their respective knock sensor voltage levels. If a knock sensor's voltage level is below its calculated threshold then that knock sensor's signal is ignored.This value is used for both knock sensors.See also: {-B6241}{-B6242}

TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Determines whether knock detection is done per cylinder or per engine.If this value is set (Cylinder Mode), then the following knock threshold multiplier tables are used:{B6244}and{B6245}If this value is not set (Engine Mode), then the following knock threshold multiplier tables are used:{B6246}and{B6247}
TableSeek.ExtraCategories: Engine Calibration - Spark - Knock Sensor - Software

TableSeek.Name: Knock_Portion
TableSeek.Description: The portion of the knock A/D reading used in the calculation of the average noise level knock event., Units: Multiplier
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: This value determines the weighting of detected knock that is used to update the average background noise value.Smaller values cause the average background noise value to change more slowly, larger values cause the average background noise value to change more quickly.The average background noise is added to the knock thresholds prior to any comparison with the detected knock sensor values.See also: {-B6249}
TableSeek.ExtraCategories: Engine Calibration - Spark - Knock Sensor - Software

TableSeek.Name: Delta_RPM_Knock_Energy_MAD*01-

TableSeek.ExtraDescription: This multiplier is applied when in RPM Knock Mode.RPM Knock Mode is active when all three RPM conditions are met: Minimum, Maximum and Delta.This value is multiplied with the learned knock threshold to determine the knock threshold voltage for the current operating conditions.If both TPS Knock Mode and RPM Knock Mode are active, the highest value will be used.Higher values desensitize the knock sensors.Lower values sensitize the knock sensors.See also: {-B6256}{-B6257}{-B6258}{-B6259}
TableSeek.ExtraCategories: Engine Calibration - Spark - Knock Sensor - Software

TableSeek.Name: Knock_Energy_MAD*01-
TableSeek.Description: This calibration is used with the Integrated energy read to determine if knock occurred., Units: Multiplier
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: B6244 - Knock Sensor Multiplier A (Cylinder Mode)
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: This multiplier is applied when not in RPM Knock Mode or TPS Knock Mode, otherwise the appropriate RPM or TPS knock multipliers are applied.This value is multiplied with the learned knock threshold to determine the knock threshold voltage for the current operating conditions.Higher values desensitize the knock sensors.Lower values sensitize the knock sensors.See also: {-B6250}{-B6255}
TableSeek.ExtraCategories: Engine Calibration - Spark - Knock Sensor - Software

TableSeek.Name: Tip_In_Knock_Energy_MAD*01-

TableSeek.ExtraCategories: Engine Calibration - Spark - Knock Sensor - Software

TableSeek.Name: Knock_Energy_MAD*01-

TableSeek.Name: MISF_Cylinder_Mode_Idle
TableSeek.Description: Maximum delta time between cylinder events expected when in cylinder mode analysis during low engine speeds and at idleconditions. By definition, a value of 100% of the range willdisable the mode., Units: Microseconds
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: C5621 - Misfire Idle per Cylinder Mode
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Maximum time limit between cylinder events at Idle that will be deemed a misfire.CASE: Cylinder Mode misfire detection takes into account the Crank Angle Sensor Error (CASE) as recorded by the PCM during a CASE learn procedure.Non-CASE: Revolution Mode misfire detection does not take into account the CASE.A value of 32767 in a cell, or immediately below or to the right of the cell, will disable misfire detection for that cell.If both CASE and Non-CASE tables contain a valid value (i.e. not 32767) for the same cell, then the Non-CASE table's value will take precedence over the CASE table's value.If the engine RPM is less than {C5620} "Misfire RPM Idle Limit" then {C5621} "Misfire Idle per Cylinder Mode" will always be used.

TableSeek.Name: Manual_Transmission_Speeds*01-
TableSeek.Description: Used to configure Class 2 3A3C transmission option message for manual transmissions., Units: Xmsn_Spd_Type
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Defines if the vehicle is fitted with 5 or 6-speed manual transmissionunchecked - 5 speed transmissionchecked - 6 speed transmission

TableSeek.Name: Reverse_Lockout_Equipped*1mb
TableSeek.Description: Set TRUE if manual transmission has reverse lockout control solenoid., Units: Boolean

TableSeek.Name: Allison_LCT_Model*01-
TableSeek.Description: Used to configure Class 2 3A3C transmission option message for Allison LCT applications., Units: Allison_LCT_Model_Type

TableSeek.Name: Force_Motor_Frequency*99-05
TableSeek.Description: Frequency at which to operate the Force Motor output., Units: Hertz

TableSeek.Name: Clutch_Switch_Type*01-
TableSeek.Description: Describes the type of clutch switch, if any, used on thevehicle., Units: No_switch/Closed to IGN/GRN

TableSeek.Name: SF_Pulses_Per_Revolution*01-
TableSeek.Description: Transmission output speed sensor scaling factor., Units: Pulses/Rev
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: H0102 - Vehicle Speed Sensor Pulses per Revolution
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: The number of pulses the speed sensor produces per single transmission output shaft (TOS) revolution, which is normally* the same as the number of teeth on the vehicle speed sensor's reluctor ring.For manual vehicles, it is not used and is sometimes set incorrectly. The normal values used for this calibration are 17 and 40.Manual gearboxes are usually 17 and automatic transmissions are usually 40. However, some trucks with manual gearboxes use 40.For automatic vehicles, it is used by the PCM to determine the transmission shift speeds and will normally be consistent with the equation: H0101=H0102*H0104.* Corvettes have this value calibrated to "40 divided by actual diff ratio" (regardless of whether they are manual or automatic) since the reluctor ring is located on the rear transaxle - not the transmission output shaft.

TableSeek.Name: SF_Max_Time_Since_Last_Pulse
TableSeek.Description: If no transmission output speed pulses have been seen for this length of time then the speed is considered to be zero., Units: Seconds
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: Max time to wait for VSS pulses
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Defines the max time between pulses that are allowed before PCM assumes vehicle stationary, or VSS inoperative.

TableSeek.Name: Neutral_Start_Switch_Equipped*1mb
TableSeek.Description: True if vehicle is equipped with a Neutral_Start_Switch or Bottom_of_Travel_Clutch_Switch., Units: Boolean

TableSeek.Name: Manual_Mode_Allowed
TableSeek.Description: This determines whether manual mode is allowed as a shift pattern., Units: BOOLEAN

TableSeek.Name: MNP_Type
TableSeek.Description: This determines how many shift pattern switches are used as input., Units: Switches
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: D0409 - Shift Pattern Mode Select Switch
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: These options enable the various shift pattern modes within the PCM.Note: J1 is the 'BLUE' connector on the PCM.Switch types used must be momentary connect to ground.'No Switch' = Performance mode via a switch is not functional.'One Switch' = Performance mode via a switch can be activated (J1 - pin71).'Two Switches' = Performance mode via a switch can be activated (J1 - pin71), and Manual Mode can be activated (J1 - pin31).'C2 Data Bus' = Shift pattern modes are sent on the data bus to the PCM from another module, eg - BCM.Only the following values may be entered into this table:0 - No Switch1 - One Switch2 - Two Switches3 - C2 Data Bus

TableSeek.Name: Reverse_Enable_On*1mb
TableSeek.Description: The vehicle speed below which reverse is allowed., Units: MPH
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: Reverse Lockout Disable Vehicle Speed MPH
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: If vehicle speed is higher than this, reverse lockout will turn on (reverse cannot be engaged).

TableSeek.Name: Reverse_Enable_Off*1mb
TableSeek.Description: The vehicle speed above which reverse is not allowed., Units: MPH
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: Reverse Lockout Enable Vehicle Speed MPH
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: If vehicle speed is lower than this, reverse lockout will turn off (reverse can be engaged).

TableSeek.Name: CARS_Bulb_Check
TableSeek.Description: Determine if the bulb check is to be used., Units: Boolean

TableSeek.Name: Execute_CARS_Algorithm
TableSeek.Description: Set to TRUE if the CARS (skip shift) logic should be executed, Units: Boolean
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: Enable/ Disable the CARS/CAGS system from functioning.Applies only to Manual Transmission calibrations.Unchecked = DisabledChecked = Enabled

TableSeek.Name: Manual_Xmsn_Has_Temp_Sensor*01-
TableSeek.Description: Flag indicating that manual transmission has a temperaturesensor, causes algorithm to detect xmsn overtemperature tobe executed., Units: Boolean

TableSeek.Name: Allison_TCM_Voltage*01-
TableSeek.Description: Voltage below which the TCM MIL request will not be monitored, Units: Volts

TableSeek.Name: TCM_Powerup_Integrity_Delay*01-
TableSeek.Description: Time after ignition on that the PCM will start monitoring theAllison TCM MIL request for line integrity check - P0802, Units: Seconds

TableSeek.Name: TCM_Powerup_Integrity_Complet*01-
TableSeek.Description: Time after ignition on that the PCM will stop monitoring theAllison TCM MIL request for line integrity check - P0802, Units: Seconds

TableSeek.Name: TCM_General_Delay_Request*01-
TableSeek.Description: Time after KE_TCM_Powerup_Integrity_Complete that the PCM willstart monitoring the Allison TCM MIL request for a generaltransmission failure - P0700, Units: Seconds

TableSeek.Name: K_Four_Wheel_Drive_Available

TableSeek.Name: K_Input_Speed_Present*01-

TableSeek.Name: Signed_Trq_Shift_Press_Enbl*01-

TableSeek.Name: 1_2_Drive_Low_Line
TableSeek.Description: Drive-Low 1st to 2nd gear upshift shift line., Units: MPH
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: This table configures the Manually Selected Gear Shifts (i.e. caused by the driver moving the Gear Shift) - Upshift and Downshift Speeds (MPH). The Upshift Speeds may be safely set to the maximum (254 MPH) - for full manual control of the Upshifts. The Downshift Speeds must be CAREFULLY set, to avoid causing damage to the Engine or the Transmission.As an example, the 2>1 Downshift:If this speed was set to the maximum (254 MPH), then if the driver manually selected 1st Gear using the Gear Shift, the Transmission would downshift at any speed - which could cause damage.This speed should be calculated to correspond to a REASONABLE RPM, in the Gear being downshifted into. The 2>1 Downshift may end up being in the 25 MPH to 40 MPH range.

TableSeek.Name: Pulses_Per_Mile*01-
TableSeek.Description: Vehicle speed sensor scaling factor., Units: Pulses/Mile
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: H0101 - Vehicle Speed Sensor Pulses per Mile
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: The number of Pulses the Speed Sensor produces per Mile. This value is used to determine the vehicle's actual Speed, and controls the Speedometer Needle in the Instrument Cluster.Increasing this value (H0101) will reduce the indicated speed of the Speedometer.Decreasing this value (H0101) will increase the indicated speed of the Speedometer.This value MUST be manually calculated by YOU. Some tuning software have an automated calculator "Wizard".H0101 is calculated using this formula: H0101 = (H0102 x H0103 x 63360) ÷ (Tire Diameter x Pi)Where:H0101 = Vehicle Speed Sensor Pulses per MileH0102 = Vehicle Speed Sensor (VSS) Pulses per Revolution (typically 17 or 40)H0103 = Axle or Differential Gear Ratio (eg. 3.73)Tire Diameter = tire diameter in inchesPi = 3.14159

TableSeek.Name: Pulses_Per_Mile*99-00
TableSeek.Description: Vehicle speed sensor scaling factor., Units: Pulses/Mile
TableSeek.ExtraTableName: H0101 - Vehicle Speed Sensor Pulses per Mile

TableSeek.Name: Use_EEPROM_VSS_Cals*01-
TableSeek.Description: Determines whether to use the EEPROM based VSS cals or the Cal ROM VSS cals., Units: BOOLEAN
TableSeek.ExtraDescription: If this calibration parameter is set, the PCM will ignore the calibrated VSS settings and will use externally programmed VSS settings instead. That means an external scan tool (such as Tech2) is required to program the VSS settings.If this calibration parameter is cleared, the PCM will use the calibrated VSS settings and will ignore any externally programmed VSS settings.
